          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a smooth and separated scheme.
    By Nagata [<fr:link type="local" href="N1962.xml" addr="N1962" title="Imbedding of an abstract variety in a complete variety">N1962</fr:link>], <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a Zariski open of a complete scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}]]></fr:tex>.
    By Hironaka [<fr:link type="local" href="H1964.xml" addr="H1964" title="Resolution of singularities of an algebraic variety over a field of characteristic zero">H1964</fr:link>], we can take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}]]></fr:tex> to be smooth and such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y=\overline {X}\setminus  X]]></fr:tex> is a normal crossing divisor.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The reader who wishes to avoid the reference to Nagata can suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> to be quasi-projective.
    
    The smooth completion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}]]></fr:tex> can then be chosen to be projective and such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is the union of smooth divisors.
    If we limit ourselves to such compactifications, then we only need Hodge theory in its standard form (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.xml" number="2.2.1" />).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
